TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years old.
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
In the documents that were in the possession of the publication, it is said that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance company) with the help of the application promotes the goals of China's foreign policy abroad.
The bulk of the violations regarding China's policies fall under "hate speech."
In each case, TikTok places unwanted publications in a context that fits the general rules, so that the actions of the social network do not look censorship.
For example, the ban on criticism of China's socialist system falls under the general prohibition of "criticizing or attacking the policies and social rules of any country, such as a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary system, etc."
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the "distortion of the history of China or other countries."
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen," including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong Un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hee, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.  is stated in the document.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may entail the blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: "Now we use a localized approach for moderation, and also attract independent local specialists."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the Production Center.
"Production Center" is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Production Center" coordinates with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without approval, bogdanov reports.
When asked whether it is possible to speak on TikTok about politics or Putin, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, the founder of Our Didgital, agrees with Bogdanov: "TikTok lists the basic rules for users in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on."
But under these rules you can bring any content that moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripov Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years old.
According to the user agreement, only persons over 13 years of age can use TikTok.
Administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how many years a person looks like, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019. ByteDance has opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the WeWork coworking space.
